Introduction

We will be using Tidyverse functions to organize and analyze timelapse proliferation data, from an Incucyte automated microscope, of several mouse pancreatic cancer cell lines. (Thank you to Shuba Narayan for doing these experiments and providing her data.) Key points of this experiment are as follows:

  • Data are measured as percent confluence within each well
  • Five cell lines total, designated: 12738, 12910, 12962, 12965 and 12969
  • Cells engineered to express either EGFP (negative control) or Ptf1a, a transcription factor that we hypothesize will inhibit their proliferation
  • Transgene expression (EGFP vs Ptf1a) is induced by doxycycline (DOX); untreated cells used as controls
  • 3 separate experiments per line, each with 3 technical replicates (i.e.replicate wells) per condition

This analysis was motivated by the finding that although several of the cell lines showed reproducible decreases in growth upon Ptf1a expression, the magnitude of the effect varied from experiment to experiment and it was hard to present the data all together in a convincing way. Could we figure out an easier way to analyze all the data, and a prettier way to graph it? (Yeah I sometimes refer to data in the singular.)

I used Excel to assemble all the Incucyte output into a single spreadsheet, Incucyte_all.txt. Data columns are named according to overexpressed gene, DOX treatment and technical replicate: thus, Ptf1a_untreated_1 refers to the first well containing cells with the Ptf1a transgene, not treated with DOX.

Note that you can do all this data assembly and variable renaming within R, using Tidyverse functions. If you have many data files, each with many columns (e.g.multiple RNA-seq read tables), reorganizing in Excel is impractical. While outside the scope of this lecture, I recommend the use of the nested dataframe approach described here: https://serialmentor.com/blog/2016/6/13/reading-and-combining-many-tidy-data-files-in-R

Data import

Okay, lets get started by loading the required R packages, clearing any pre-existing data, and reading in the dataset. When you run this code, be sure that the working directory has been set to wherever Incucyte_all.txt is located:

library(tidyverse)  # functions for tidy data manipulation
library(cowplot)    # pretty-looking graphs
rm(list=ls())  # clear the decks
options(stringsAsFactors = FALSE)  # useful option for non-Tidyverse work

data_wide <- read_tsv('Incucyte_all.txt') %>% print()

## #   Ptf1a_DOX_3 <dbl>

If you are used to base R, there are already three weird things here.

  1. I used Tidyverse command read_tsv, which reads a tab-separated text file into a data frame. You could get almost the same result using the base R command read.table('Incucyte_all.txt', sep='\t').

  2. The only difference from read.table is that read_tsv formats the data frame into a tibble, a fancier data frame structure that makes it much easier to quickly look at the contents. When you print the contents of a tibble, it shows you only what fits on your console screen, while also telling you what other variables and rows exist. Try importing the same data via read.table and then printing it - its kind of a mess. Now imagine that your data has 100 or 1000 columns, and think about how it would look in base R! Importantly, though, all base R functions work normally on tibbles, its just that tibbles look nicer on the screen.

  3. I ended the line with %>% print(), a great trick I learned on Twitter from Stephen Turner at UVA: https://twitter.com/strnr/status/1047203915232661505. It uses the pipe operator %>% (keyboard shortcut: ctrl-shift-M) to print the output of whatever else your line of code was doing. It does not alter any other work done by the code (e.g.assigning or modifying variables), and it is a quick and easy way to check your work on the fly.

Data tidying

Now, back to our data. Lets reorganize it into tidy format, i.e.one row per data point, with confluence data as the measured variable.

The key command here is gather, for which you need to provide four arguments: gather(data, key, value, ...) (check the help entry for additional options)

  1. data is just the wide (spreadsheet-type) data that you wish to convert - in our case, helpfully named data_wide
  2. key is the name you want to use for your new descriptor column, i.e.the names that are currently used for each data column in your spreadsheet - we will call it treatment_group
  3. value is the name you want to use for your new data column - in this case, we are measuring the confluence of individual wells, so we will use that name
  4. ... is where you specify what columns in your spreadsheet contain the data - our first data column is labeled EGFP_untreated_1 and the last is Ptf1a_DOX_3, so we will specify this selection with: EGFP_untreated_1:Ptf1a_DOX_3

Note that there are more sophisticated ways to select specific columns using the Tidyverse function select, which you should read up on.

# convert wide data to narrow/tidy format
data_narrow <- gather(data_wide, key='treatment_group', value='confluence', EGFP_untreated_1:Ptf1a_DOX_3) %>%
  print()
## # A tibble: 6,636 x 6

Generating new grouping variables with separate

treatment_group combines multiple data labels into one (as one is forced to do when working with wide/spreadsheet-style data), which would be much easier to analyze separately. So lets use the extremely useful Tidyverse command separate.

# split treatment_group variable into separate variables for overexpressed gene, treatment, and replicate
data_narrow <- separate(data_narrow, treatment_group, c('gene', 'treatment', 'rep')) %>% print()
## # A tibble: 6,636 x 8
##     Line Elapsed   Date Experiment gene  treatment rep   confluence
##    <dbl>   <dbl>  <dbl>      <dbl> <chr> <chr>     <chr>      <dbl>
##  1 12738       0 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           16.2
##  2 12738       2 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           18.1
##  3 12738       4 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           17.5
##  4 12738       6 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           18.0
##  5 12738       8 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           18.4
##  6 12738      10 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           19.4
##  7 12738      12 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           20.1
##  8 12738      14 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           21.3
##  9 12738      16 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           22.3
## 10 12738      18 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           23.1

separate defaults to splitting a string of text up by any non-alphanumeric value, so it would work equally well with EGFP.untreated.1 or even EGFP:untreated-1. But if you want to specify the separator, e.g.if you have some punctuation you want to preserve (EGFP!_untreated_1), then you can pass the argument sep='_'.

We will also convert the treatment info into an ordered factor, so that when we plot the data, R will know to graph untreated cells first, then DOX (i.e.control first, then experimental). (Since EGFP is alphabetically ahead of Ptf1a, R will know to graph them in that order, but you could also convert this variable into an ordered factor if you preferred a different order.) For this, we will use the mutate command, another one of the MVPs of the Tidyverse.

Creating new columns or changing existing ones with mutate - a toy example

mutate is used to create a column in a data frame based on an operation of an existing column. For example, lets imagine we have a series of temperature measurements in Farenheit that we would like to convert to Celsius:

# create toy data
temp_df <- bind_cols(sample=c(1,2,3), temp=c(-40, 32, 98.6)) %>% print()
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   sample  temp
##    <dbl> <dbl>
## 1      1 -40  
## 2      2  32  
## 3      3  98.6
# use "mutate" to create new column with temperature in Celsius
temp_df <- mutate(temp_df, tempC=(temp-32)*5/9) %>% print()
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   sample  temp tempC
##    <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1      1 -40     -40
## 2      2  32       0
## 3      3  98.6    37

Alternatively, we could have simply replaced the old temp variable with a new variable of the same name, but converted to Celsius, with: temp_df <- mutate(temp_df, temp=(temp-32)*5/9). This is the approach we will use with data_narrow, below. Before we get to that, lets check out a nice trick with mutate, where we can refer back, within the same command, to a new column that weve just created. Well also use the pipe operator (%>%) and the Tidyverse function rename to clean up the column names at the end.

A key point about %>%: the next function after the pipe will know that you are sending it data, so you dont need to (in fact, cannot) specify the name of the data on which you want to operate. For example, this will work: temp_df$tempC %>% mean() but this will give you an error: temp_df$tempC %>% mean(temp_df$tempC)

# create toy data, again
temp_df <- bind_cols(time=c(1,2,3), temp=c(-40, 32, 98.6))

# now let's add both Celsius and Kelvin temperatures in one command
temp_df <- mutate(temp_df, tempC=(temp-32)*5/9, tempK=tempC+273.15) %>%
  rename(tempF = temp) %>%  # and also rename original variable "temp" to "tempF"
  print()
## # A tibble: 3 x 4
##    time tempF tempC tempK
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     1 -40     -40  233.
## 2     2  32       0  273.
## 3     3  98.6    37  310.

Just for comparison, here is how you might replicate the above manipulation of Incucyte_all.txt without using Tidyverse functions (even figuring this out required multiple trips to StackExchange):

# for comparison to base R approach, read original data via "read.delim" function
data_baseR <- read.delim('Incucyte_all.txt', sep='\t')

# note that the only easy way to convert a wide data frame to narrow, outside of the Tidyverse, is using
# the "melt" command from the "reshape" package - which is something Hadley Wickham developed before he
# came up with the extended Tidyverse
data_narrow_baseR <- reshape::melt.data.frame(data_baseR, id.vars=c('Line', 'Elapsed', 'Date', 'Experiment'),
                                            variable_name='treatment_group')
# note that "melt" doesn't let you specify the name of the variable column, it just calls it "value"
#   by default - so we have to manually rename it as 'confluence'
colnames(data_narrow_baseR)[colnames(data_narrow_baseR)=='value'] <- 'confluence'

# now, let's split up the "treatment_group" variable
# first, though, we need to convert "treatment_group" from a factor variable (the dumb default behavior
#   of melt) to character
data_narrow_baseR$treatment_group <- as.character(data_narrow_baseR$treatment_group)
# then we split treatment_group into a list, aka the most unintuitive data type in R
l <- strsplit(data_narrow_baseR$treatment_group, '_')  
# then we convert the list into a matrix, with three columns
m <- matrix(unlist(l), nrow=length(l), ncol=3, byrow=T)  
# convert the matrix into a data frame
df <- data.frame(m)
colnames(df) <- c('gene', 'treatment', 'rep')  # and give the columns of the data frame the names we want

# finally, reassemble our original data frame with our new columns replacing the original "treatment_group"
data_narrow_baseR <- cbind(data_narrow_baseR[c('Line', 'Elapsed', 'Date', 'Experiment')], df,
                         data_narrow_baseR['confluence'])

# let's compare base R data frame to the original Tidyverse one
print(head(data_narrow_baseR))

Wrangling and exploring our data

Now that weve loaded our data, we want to address the question underlying our experiment: does Ptf1a overexpression inhibit proliferation of pancreatic cancer cell lines?

A first figure

First, lets just see what the raw confluence over time data looks like, using ggplot. The basic code is similar to what we saw in lecture last week, with a few new tricks:

  • We want to plot the individual data points, which is trivial, as well as the lines connecting them, which is less trivial than it sounds: we need to specifiy a group variable in the aesthetics, which indicates which points should be connected, and in this case we want to connect all the points for each experiment, for each gene, for each treatment condition (-/+ DOX), and for each replicate. Therefore we include group=interaction(Experiment, gene, treatment, rep)) in the initial aes call. interaction is a very useful base R function, which you should read up on.
  • We use interaction again in defining the colors: to make things semi-readable, I am using light vs dark colors for -/+ DOX, and green vs.orange-red for GFP vs.Ptf1a. You can specify colors via scale_color_manual, and in fact most graphing attributes can be controlled via various scale functions.
  • Finally, we call facet_wrap in the last line to split up the plots according to cell line. We know that the different lines proliferate at different rates, so plotting all the data together will inevitably look messy. (Try it yourself, though!)
fig1 <- ggplot(data_narrow,
               aes(x=Elapsed, y=confluence,
                   group=interaction(Experiment, gene, treatment, rep),
                   color=interaction(gene, treatment))) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.7) +
  geom_line(alpha=0.7) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('greenyellow', 'orange', 'green4', 'orangered3')) +
  theme(aspect.ratio=1, 
        legend.position='top',
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.text = element_text(size=10)) +
  facet_wrap(facets=vars(Line), scales='free')

fig1

Well, this looks like hot garbage at first glance, although maybe there is something happening in a couple of lines: in 12738 and 12910, at least there are a bunch of slow-proliferating samples with Ptf1a +DOX, consistent with our hypothesis. But there are also several Ptf1a +DOX samples tucked in with the faster-proliferating samples, so is this just an artifact?

Summarizing our data with summarize - a toy example

We will first need to combine the technical replicates within each experiment, which was of course the reason we did technical replicates to begin with. This will involve two more key players within the Tidyverse, group_by and summarize. To see how these work, lets first use a toy example from mpg, a pre-loaded dataset (in tibble format) from the Tidyverse that has fuel economy data from 1999-2008 for 38 car models. Lets figure out how many models have 4 vs 6 vs 8 cylinders, and calculate the mean and standard deviation of their mileage and horsepower.

data(mpg)
print(mpg)  # just to check what the data look like

##    manufacturer model displ  year   cyl trans drv     cty   hwy fl    class

##  1 audi         a4      1.8  1999     4 auto f        18    29 p     comp
##  2 audi         a4      1.8  1999     4 manu f        21    29 p     comp
##  3 audi         a4      2    2008     4 manu f        20    31 p     comp

First we need to group the data, in this case by cylinder, using group_by. This doesnt change the data frame, but it imposes a layer of organization that we can use when we want to perform groupwise calculations, using summarize.

# first we need to group the cars
mpg_by_cyl <- group_by(mpg, cyl) %>% print()
## # A tibble: 234 x 11
## # Groups:   cyl [4]
##    manufacturer model displ  year   cyl trans drv     cty   hwy fl    class

##  2 audi         a4      1.8  1999     4 manu f        21    29 p     comp
##  3 audi         a4      2    2008     4 manu f        20    31 p     comp
##  4 audi         a4      2    2008     4 auto f        21    30 p     comp
##  5 audi         a4      2.8  1999     6 auto f        16    26 p     comp
##  6 audi         a4      2.8  1999     6 manu f        18    26 p     comp
##  7 audi         a4      3.1  2008     6 auto f        18    27 p     comp
##  8 audi         a4 q   1.8  1999     4 manu 4        18    26 p     comp
##  9 audi         a4 q   1.8  1999     4 auto 4        16    25 p     comp
## 10 audi         a4 q   2    2008     4 manu 4        20    28 p     comp
## #  with 224 more rows
# this has created a new tibble, but we can easily confirm that all elements of the data frame itself
#   are preserved from the original:
table(mpg_by_cyl==mpg)
## 
## TRUE 
## 2574

Now, the main event. Calling summarize allows us to perform as many groupwise operations as we want, and it will spit out a new data frame in which the grouping variable is on the left, followed by the output of whatever operations we performed. In this case, we will count the numbers of models within each cylinder group (n), and the mean and standard deviation (sd) of their highway mileage hwy and engine displacement displ.

# identify and summarize car models within each cylinder group
mpg_cyl_summarize <- summarize(mpg_by_cyl,
                               n=n(), hwy_mean=mean(hwy), hwy_sd=sd(hwy), 
                               displ_mean=mean(displ), displ_sd=sd(displ))
print(mpg_cyl_summarize)
## # A tibble: 4 x 6
##     cyl     n hwy_mean hwy_sd displ_mean displ_sd
##   <int> <int>    <dbl>  <dbl>      <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1     4    81     28.8   4.52       2.15    0.315
## 2     5     4     28.8   0.5        2.5     0    
## 3     6    79     22.8   3.69       3.41    0.472
## 4     8    70     17.6   3.26       5.13    0.589

Hopefully this makes sense! (Also: who knew that there were five-cylinder engines?) But before we go back to the Incucyte data, lets also see how easy it is to use the %>% pipe operator to get the same results without creating a bunch of new variables, while also preserving readable code.

# first, without creating a new data frame, we will call "group_by" on the original data,
#   then pipe it to "summarize"
group_by(mpg, cyl) %>% 
  summarize(n=n(), hwy_mean=mean(hwy), hwy_sd=sd(hwy), displ_mean=mean(displ), displ_sd=sd(displ))
## # A tibble: 4 x 6
##     cyl     n hwy_mean hwy_sd displ_mean displ_sd
##   <int> <int>    <dbl>  <dbl>      <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1     4    81     28.8   4.52       2.15    0.315
## 2     5     4     28.8   0.5        2.5     0    
## 3     6    79     22.8   3.69       3.41    0.472
## 4     8    70     17.6   3.26       5.13    0.589

This is a great way to perform basic data exploration.

Back to our data - combining technical replicates

Hopefully it is obvious what we need to do with our Incucyte data_narrow, but lets first remind ourselves what the data look like.

print(data_narrow)
## # A tibble: 6,636 x 8
##     Line Elapsed   Date Experiment gene  treatment rep   confluence
##    <dbl>   <dbl>  <dbl>      <dbl> <chr> <fct>     <chr>      <dbl>
##  1 12738       0 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           16.2
##  2 12738       2 180116          1 EGFP  untreated 1           18.1

We want to combine each set of technical replicates, which means we need to group_by every other grouping variable - if we dont include gene in our grouping, for example, the summarize function will eventually smoosh together the EGFP and Ptf1a results. R is smart enough to be very stupid, if we dont give it careful instructions!

Then we will call mean and sd on the summarized data, and return the compressed data frame - and confirm that it is 1/3 the size of the original, due to compressing the triplicate data points.

# calculate mean confluence across technical replicates
data_mean <- group_by(data_narrow, Line, Experiment, Date, Elapsed, gene, treatment) %>%
  summarize(conf_mean=mean(confluence), conf_sd=sd(confluence)) %>% print()
## # A tibble: 2,212 x 8

## 10 12738          1 180116       4 EGFP  DOX            19.8   2.06 
## #  with 2,202 more rows
data_mean <- ungroup(data_mean)  # this will be necessary later. and is a good idea generally

# the new data frame should be 1/3 the length of the original, since the triple replicates have been
#   collapsed down to one each - let's confirm
nrow(data_mean) == nrow(data_narrow)/3
## [1] TRUE

Data inspection

Before we go back to growth curves, we can take a quick look at the data to see if there are any systematic errors present - e.g.is one of the conditions plagued by an unusual amount of variation? I find it useful to plot the coefficient of variation, \(CV=SD/mean\), which is sort of a normalized standard deviation, as a function of the mean. In theory, all the samples should have similar CVs, and if we see that one set of samples stands out for for having unusually high CVs, it may indicate a systematic error (e.g.we only plated two wells instead of three). Here we will plot mean vs.CV for all observations, color-coded by cell line, transgene or DOX treatment status.

# first, add CV as a column to our data frame
data_mean <- mutate(data_mean, conf_cv=conf_sd/conf_mean)

# create base plot
p <- ggplot(data_mean, aes(x=conf_mean, y=conf_cv))

# plot with various color coding schemes
p_line <- p + geom_point(aes(color=factor(Line)), alpha=0.5, size=1)
p_gene <- p + geom_point(aes(color=gene), alpha=0.5, size=1)
p_treatment <- p + geom_point(aes(color=treatment), alpha=0.5, size=1)

plot_grid(p_line, p_gene, p_treatment, align='h')

Two points to note:

  • The plots are not just straight horizontal lines, and in fact there is a hint of an arc shape starting at the lower-left, curving up and then back down to the lower-right. If you think about what we are measuring (proliferation of cells within a fixed surface area), this may make sense.
  • There is quite a bit of spread, especially on the left half of the graph, but there is no sign of systematic error, i.e.no condition is consistently associated with higher CV. This is real-world data, and sometimes things are noisy. The most variable samples dont look like outliers.

Note that the above is a very amateurish approach to data inspection, but it is worth putting in at least some effort, early on, to make sure that your data doesnt have some major problem that could later make it uninterpretable. The use of ggplot makes it particularly easy to see whether any grouping/descriptor variables, e.g.sex or genotype, is associated with large changes or aberrations in the data.

A second figure

Now, lets plot the mean and SD (as error bar) of each cell line/experiment. As before, we will plot individual points as well as lines connecting them - note that since we have collapsed the technical replicates into conf_mean, our group=interaction call needs only connect Experiment, gene and treatment.

fig2 <- ggplot(data_mean, aes(x=Elapsed, y=conf_mean, 
                              group=interaction(Experiment, gene, treatment),
                              color=interaction(gene, treatment))) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.7) +
  geom_line(alpha=0.7) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=conf_mean-conf_sd, ymax=conf_mean+conf_sd)) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('greenyellow', 'orange', 'green4', 'orangered3')) +
  expand_limits(y=0) +
  theme(aspect.ratio=1, 
        legend.position='top',
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.text = element_text(size=10)) +
  facet_wrap(facets=vars(Line), scales='free')

fig2

Things are starting to look a little cleaner, but there is still the confounding fact that in some cell lines, only some but not all of the Ptf1a +DOX samples appear to be slow-growing.

One potential explanation: between experiments, there appears to be inconsistency in terms of how confluent the cells were at the start of the experiment: if slow-growing cells were initially twice as dense, in one experiment, as fast-growing cells in another experiment, the difference in their growth kinetics might be hard to see.

Lets do a quick bit of data exploration with another key Tidyverse function, filter.

Examining subsets of data with filter - a toy example

filter is called with filter(data, ...,), where data is, of course, your data frame of interest, and ... is one or more logical arguments with which to evaluate your data. It returns a data frame containing the rows of data that satisfy the arguments in .... Lets go back to our mpg data for a toy example.

We want to ask: what carmakers make the best (top 25%) highway mileage models with automatic transmission? To answer this, we will perform the following operations:

  1. filter for automatic transmission models - using the awesome Tidyverse string-handling function str_detect on the trans column
  2. filter again, now for models with hwy mileage above the 75th percentile (using base R function quantile)
  3. count the number of models made per manufacturer
  4. plot the result as a barplot, calling reorder to rank manufacturers by number of models
# filter mpg data for top 25% highest highway mileage of automatic transmission cars, and graph
#   the number of models per manufacturer
filter(mpg, str_detect(trans, 'auto')) %>% 
  filter(hwy > quantile(hwy, 0.75)) %>%
  count(manufacturer) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(manufacturer, -n), y=n)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    xlab('manufacturer') +
    ylab('number of models')

Ive used %>% liberally in the above example, because of my fetish for R aesthetics, but you could get the same results just creating new data frames at each step, which also gives you more room to check how your code is working at each step:

Now it looks like something interesting is happening: in lines 12738, 12910 and 19262, there are Ptf1 +DOX samples that start out at a relatively high confluence, but end up lower than their t=0 neighbors. The results with 12965 are mixed, while in 12969 there seems to be no difference between Ptf1a +DOX and the others.

But we still would like to look at these data as actual curves. Maybe the right way to approach it would be to normalize each experiment to its starting point, i.e.express the data in terms of fold-change relative to t=0.

Transforming our data by normalization to starting values

Approach:

  1. create a new data frame containing the t=0 data, baseline, with conf_mean renamed to initial
  2. merge baseline into data_mean data frame via inner_join - this will add the t=0 confluence as a new column, initial
  3. create fold-normalized confluence by dividing conf_mean by initial - similar operation for standard deviation values
  4. graph the results

Note that this is the first time that we are actually transforming our data, which is a step you should always think hard about - does it make sense to do this, or could I be introducing a new and unrecognized source of error? Ill come back to this briefly at the very end.

# create new data frame for initial confluence values, get rid of extraneous columns
baseline <- filter(data_mean, Elapsed==0) %>% 
  rename(initial=conf_mean) %>%
  select(-Elapsed, -conf_sd, -conf_cv) %>% print()

Summarizing data across experiments

Now that we have transformed our data in a way that makes sense, it would be appropriate to pool across experiments, i.e.determine the mean and SD of the biological replicates (at this point we are still plotting error bars corresponding to technical replicates).

# calculate mean fold-change (and SD) across experiments
data_fold_mean <- group_by(data_fold, Line, Elapsed, gene, treatment) %>% 
  summarize(fold_mean=mean(fold), fold_mean_sd=sd(fold)) %>% print()

Now this is looking relatively convincing: lines 12738, 12910 and 12962 all show a clear and specific inhibition of growth with Ptf1a expression, while the other two lines are weakly or non-responsive to Ptf1a.

Just to pretty things up and give our eyes something to grab on to (and which we can potentially use for statistical analysis down the road), lets calculate the half-maximal net growth within each cell lines, and add it to the plot as a horizontal line. We can then compare long it takes for each line to reach a set growth point, well before any of them hits confluence. Note that there are R packages for formal statistical analyses of growth data, such as growthcurver, and you can also use R to estimate the time to half-maximal growth using a statistical model (e.g. loess) and the predict function - but thankfully thats way outside the scope of this lecture!

# calculate maximum mean fold change within each cell line, add half-max value to graphs
max_mean <- group_by(data_fold_mean, Line) %>% summarize(max=max(fold_mean)) %>% print()
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##    Line   max
##   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 12738  5.51
## 2 12910 16.6 
## 3 12962  8.83
## 4 12965 13.3 
## 5 12969  7.05
fig4 <- fig4 + geom_hline(data=max_mean, aes(yintercept=max/2), col='darkgray', lty='dashed')

To quote the Virginia Slims cigarette ad, youve come a long way, baby.

As a last word, though, please note that this all remains extremely naive from both statistical and biological standpoints. Can one legitimately convert confluence, a percentage measurement, to a scale-free fold-change value? In Fig. 3-4, one can clearly see several lines hitting a vertical ceiling, indicating that the cells have already reached full confluence hours before the end of the experiment - does this really mean that they have stopped dividing (cancer cells are usually relatively insenstive to contact inhibition)? And how should you compare these to samples in which cells keep expanding through the full 72-hour timecourse?

These are important considerations, and have motivated us to make changes to our experimental approach, e.g.trying to count individual cells per field rather than fractional confluence, and taking measures to understand and minimize the spread of initial cell density values. But although these changes are making the raw data somewhat cleaner, the numbers will still need to be wrangled, cleaned up and transformed in order to generate publication-quality figures, as well as to provide an entry point to actual statistical analysis, and this Tidyverse workflow will remain a useful approach.
